## [**Language Models as Planning Modelers – A Survey**](https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.18971)

[LLMs as Planning Modelers: A Survey for Leveraging Large Language Models to Construct Automated Planning Models.pdf](https://drive.google.com/open?id=1tJYcW3uMvqROSPg1bUspvNMjjh1Z_2EJ)

Authors: Marcus Tantakoun, Xiaodan Zhu, Christian Muise

Venue / Source: arXiv

Year: 2025

Link: https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.18971

Topic / Focus: Survey on using LLMs for symbolic and model-based planning.

Main Contribution / Method: Covers how LLMs can assist in planning model creation, plan refinement, and policy learning, with discussion on current limitations.

Relation to Our Project:

- It’s a good overwiev of research around LLM as part of planing  
  - Mostly focusing on the solutions that uses: Planning Domain Definition Language (PDDL)  
    - DF \- Domain definition (How we believe the world is working)   
    - PF \- Problem definition (The current state and target state of the world)  
- Solution in Papers are classified into:  
  - Task modeling \- AI generates goals and initial state in given defined domain  
  - Domain modeling \- AI Generates believes about the world   
  - Hybrid \- AI generates both goals and beliefs  
- A good amount of interesting papers   
  - Can be seen in notebookLM under [Relevant LLM-Symbolic Planning Papers from the survey](https://notebooklm.google.com/notebook/480aea4a-15e1-4c18-9003-43f6c10198a8)  
- Language2Plan (L2P), an open-source Python library


Strengths & Limitations:

- Limitations  
  - Only focusing on PDDL  
  - L2P is only for Fully observabled domains

## [**\[2409.15915\] Planning in the Dark: LLM-Symbolic Planning Pipeline without Experts**](https://arxiv.org/abs/2409.15915)

[Planning in the Dark LLM-Symbolic Planning Pipeline without Experts.pdf](https://drive.google.com/open?id=1iFkUDmJ7ac6vlVgU6gnIm3EObWGI83QO)

Authors: Sukai Huang et al.

Venue / Source: arXiv

Year: 2024

Link: https://arxiv.org/abs/2402.14642

Topic / Focus: Automating symbolic planning without expert input.

Main Contribution / Method: Proposes pipeline generating symbolic action schemas from LLMs and using semantic validation with symbolic planners.

Relation to Our Project:

- combine LLM and symbolic planer to creat a pipeline  
- pipeline: human specified prompt in NL \-\> X LLM initiated differently is generating PDDL schemas \-\> automatic check out which schemes are solvable \-\> we	 encode the sheamas using encoder and calculate cosine similarity in between user prompt and schemas \-\> this way we end up with plans that are highly correlated with the original prompt

Strengths & Limitations:

- Lack the common sense when solving a problem  
  - Example in dungeon environment   
    - task get the key and go out of the dungeon  
    - Symbolic planer do that, but doesn’t get any other loot because is not needed for the goal

## **LLaMAR: Long-Horizon Planning for Multi-Agent Robotics**

[LLaMAR: Long-Horizon Planning for Multi-Agent Robots in Partially Observable Environments](https://drive.google.com/open?id=1XkBtRHjqYDJ8ZN-vR47ND-kDJMPrp9Po)

Authors: Siddharth Nayak et al.

Venue / Source: arXiv

Year: 2024

Link: https://arxiv.org/abs/2402.01898

Topic / Focus: Planning and control for multi-agent robotics using LLMs.

Main Contribution / Method: Proposes a modular architecture with LLM-driven planning, correction, and verification modules to improve long-term task success.

Relation to Our Project:

- The paper introduces framework for long horizon planing in multi agent env  
  - The main idea is that agent can learn from the action that they take in the world and improve based on error  
  - The framework divide planing into 4 modules done by 4 LLM  with different specialisation (Plan \-\> Act \-\> correct \-\> Verify   
    - Planner — Decompose Task into subgoals based on memory and current input from agents  
    - Actor — Decides how to progress on the subgoal based on the current input and action suggestion from the Corrector  
    - Corrector — Self correct errors with ressoing for failure and proposition of improvement   
    - Verifier — Based on succesful action Check if any subgoals have been completed   
  - Interesting they used cosine similarity for the encoding  
    - of LLM generated action and the available action to match them  
    - of Image and the subgoal to guide exploration  
      - fx robot has to find a computer but doesn’t see any right now \-\> it will go into direction that(the image of the camera) has the highest cosine similarity   
  - It’s centralised planning freamwork so every agent shear the same knowledge   
    - Increasing the number of agent increase the work done but reduce the balance of work (some agent work less then others)  
    - would be interesting to see what happens the planing is not centralised but agent can still communicate 

Strengths & Limitations:

## **Generative Agents: Interactive Simulacra of Human Behavior**

[Generative Agents Interactive Simulacra of Human Behavior.pdf](https://drive.google.com/open?id=1kDOTfgPRH5BWt_6GzlMBOGN2HxhID70n)

Authors: Joon Sung Park et al.

Venue / Source: CHI / arXiv

Year: 2023

Link: https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.17580

Topic / Focus: Simulation of believable social agents using LLMs.

Main Contribution / Method: Develops agents with memory, reflection, and planning layers to simulate consistent long-term behavior in sandbox environments.

Relation to Our Project:

- We want to use it as the playground for our study   
- They create a simulation of social bechavors using LLM  
  - Each agent starts with one paragraph of description (We can improve that)  
  - They operate using following mechanism  
    - Planner (We can improve that) \- Hierarchical planing first starts from general things to do during the day and then recursively makes more fine-grained plans  
    - Memory stream and retrieval \- there is a very detailed log of things that happened during the day, that agent can retrieve. Retrieval works based on 3 scores  
      - Semantic score  
      - How recent is the event  
      - The self reported priority of the event  
    - Reflection \- agent can reflect on their actions memory and even reflection to refine internal knowledge
